  childSummary:"Your brain has 86 billion tiny cells called neurons that talk to each other using ELECTRICAL signals — like little sparks! Every time you think about moving your hand, specific neurons fire in a specific PATTERN. A Brain-Computer Interface (BCI) is a device that LISTENS to these patterns using tiny sensors either placed on your head (like a headband) or, for much better results, actually implanted inside your brain! An AI computer then TRANSLATES these brain patterns into actions: 'oh, that pattern means the person wants to move the cursor LEFT!' In 2024, Neuralink put a tiny chip in a paralyzed man's brain — and now he can play chess, video games, and browse the internet just by THINKING about it! He can't move his body, but the chip reads his brain signals and controls the computer for him. It's like having a translator between your brain's language and the computer's language!",
  applications:["Communication restoration for paralyzed/locked-in patients","Thought-controlled computer cursors and keyboards","Robotic prosthetic arm/hand control","Speech synthesis from brain signals (for ALS patients)","Cochlear implants (hearing restoration — 1M+ implanted)","Deep brain stimulation (Parkinson's, depression, epilepsy)","Neurofeedback for meditation and focus training","Brain-controlled wheelchairs and smart home devices","Visual prosthetics (restoring sight via cortical stimulation)","Research tool for understanding brain function"],
